erator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:30:\"https://wordpress.org/?v=4.5.2\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"item\";a:12:{i:0;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:42:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:5:{s:0:\"\";a:7:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:48:\"Displaying alternative content to ad block users\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:75:\"https://wpadvancedads.com/displaying-alternative-content-to-ad-block-users/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:84:\"https://wpadvancedads.com/displaying-alternative-content-to-ad-block-users/#comments\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Mon, 02 May 2016 09:55:59 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:14:\"Update Notices\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:34:\"https://wpadvancedads.com/?p=16891\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:558:\"<p>When an ad block user visits your site, he might not see the ad you have prepared for them, but instead see a blank spot. This is a challenge all publishers face and therefore it is the most popular feature request for Advanced Ads right now. I am going to address this issue as soon [&#8230;]</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/displaying-alternative-content-to-ad-block-users/\">Displaying alternative content to ad block users</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com\">Advanced Ads</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:6:\"Thomas\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:2336:\"<p>When an ad block user visits your site, he might not see the ad you have prepared for them, but instead see a blank spot. This is a challenge all publishers face and therefore it is the most popular feature request for Advanced Ads right now.</p>\n<p>I am going to address this issue as soon as possible, but in order to do it right, I wanted to ask you for your feedback regarding two important questions.</p>\n<h2>Where to set the alternative content?</h2>\n<p>Advanced Ads has three structural elements: ads, groups and placements. For a better usability, I will only add the option to enter content displayed to ad block users for one of these structural elements. Which one, is still open for discussion. I only believe that it doesnt make sense on a group level, since many users dont actually use or need them, but maybe I am wrong.</p>\n<p>Please vote for the level on which you would like to be able to select the content displayed to ad blockers in the following poll:</p>\nNote: There is a poll embedded within this post, please visit the site to participate in this post\'s poll.\n<p>If you have another idea, please share it in the comments below.</p>\n<h2>Choosing another ad or custom input?</h2>\n<p>The second question is whether there should be a plain input field for the ad blocker content or you want to actually select another ad to be displayed, when ad blockers are activated.</p>\n<p>Of course, the alternative ad needs to be undetectable, like custom html code or an image not named banner or so, but especially when you want to reuse the alternative ad blocker content, this seems to be a flexible option.</p>\n<p>Please select your favorite option below:</p>\nNote: There is a poll embedded within this post, please visit the site to participate in this post\'s poll.\n<p>If you have another idea, please share it in the comments below.</p>\n<p>Please note, that I am only going to accept comments regarding this post. If you have a support question, please <a href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/support/\">contact me through support</a>.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/displaying-alternative-content-to-ad-block-users/\">Displaying alternative content to ad block users</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com\">Advanced Ads</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:36:\"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/\";a:1:{s:10:\"commentRss\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:80:\"https://wpadvancedads.com/displaying-alternative-content-to-ad-block-users/feed/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:38:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/\";a:1:{s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1:\"4\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:1;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:33:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:3:{s:0:\"\";a:6:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:28:\"How to enable Page-level ads\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:55:\"https://wpadvancedads.com/how-to-enable-page-level-ads/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Thu, 28 Apr 2016 08:16:34 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:9:\"Tutorials\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:34:\"https://wpadvancedads.com/?p=16551\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:299:\"<p>How to activate Page-level ads on your WordPress site with just one click.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/how-to-enable-page-level-ads/\">How to enable Page-level ads</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com\">Advanced Ads</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:6:\"Thomas\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:3216:\"<p>In April 2016, AdSense enabled the new Page-level ads for all its users. If you were wondering how to monetize mobile traffic more efficiently, this might be the answer.</p>\n<p>Advanced Ads has a feature embedded that allows you to implement Page-level ads into your site with just one click. While you find the tutorial below, you can check out my <a href=\"http://webgilde.com/en/adsense-page-level-ads-test/\">review on Page-level ads</a> in order to learn if this is worth a try or not.</p>\n<h2>How to implement Page-level ads</h2>\n<h3>Enabling Page-level ads in your AdSense account</h3>\n<p>Before using Page-level ads on your site, you need to go to your AdSense account and activate them.</p>\n<p>Youll find them under <em>My Ads &gt; Content &gt; Page-level ads</em>.</p>\n<p>Page-level ads come in two formats. As <em>Anchor/overlay ads</em> which are very similar to our Sticky ads, but only sticky at the bottom of the page on mobile devices.</p>\n<p>Vignette ads are rather a full overlay, much like our <a href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/add-ons/popup-and-layer-ads/\">PopUp Ads</a>. Both formats are only working on high end mobile devices and not showing up on every page impression. They also dont count for the 3-ads-per-page limit.</p>\n<figure id=\"attachment_16552\" style=\"width: 598px\" class=\"wp-caption aligncenter\"><a href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/how-to-enable-page-level-ads/page-level-ads/\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-16552\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-16552\" src=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/page-level-ads.png\" alt=\"Page-level ads types\" width=\"598\" height=\"325\" srcset=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/page-level-ads.png 598w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/page-level-ads-300x163.png 300w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/page-level-ads-60x33.png 60w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/page-level-ads-150x82.png 150w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 598px) 100vw, 598px\" /></a><figcaption class=\"wp-caption-text\">Page-level Ads settings with Vignette Ads enabled</figcaption></figure>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h2>Implement Page-level Ads in your WordPress site</h2>\n<p>Once you activated at least one of the ad formats, you should switch to your WordPress dashboard and navigate to <em>Advanced Ads &gt; Settings &gt; AdSense</em>.</p>\n<p>If you didnt include your AdSense ID, now is a good time to do that. You can find details about it <a href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/manual/adsense-ads/\">here</a>.</p>\n<p>Now, you only need to activate the <em>Activate Page-Level ads</em> option and save the settings and the ad tag will be implemented on your site.</p>\n<h3>Test the Page-level ad tag</h3>\n<p>Since ads only show up occasionally on mobile, you can go back to the Page-level ad page in your AdSense account, scroll down and use the <em>Test it out</em> button to test if the Page-level tag is implemented. If not, please review the settings again or update your cache.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/how-to-enable-page-level-ads/\">How to enable Page-level ads</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com\">Advanced Ads</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:2;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:33:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:3:{s:0:\"\";a:6:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:61:\"Manage revenue share on multi-author blogs  ads per author\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:69:\"https://wpadvancedads.com/manage-revenue-share-on-mulit-author-blogs/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Wed, 09 Mar 2016 15:45:11 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:9:\"Tutorials\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:34:\"https://wpadvancedads.com/?p=12616\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:379:\"<p>How to display ads based on the posts author and create a revenue share model with authors on your blog.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/manage-revenue-share-on-mulit-author-blogs/\">Manage revenue share on multi-author blogs  ads per author</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com\">Advanced Ads</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:6:\"Thomas\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:3957:\"<p>A very popular feature request was to allow a revenue share with authors. For example, on an ad position within posts, you could show the authors ad 20% of the time and 80% the ads from the publisher. This would allow authors to earn more from successful posts and also motive them to create more attention to their posts.</p>\n<p>After thinking about this for a while, I decided against adding a specific feature. Especially since version 1.7 of Advanced Ads has a display conditions that allows to display ads only on posts from a specific author.</p>\n<h2>1. Create ad units</h2>\n<p>The easiest solution for a revenue share with authors would be to create ad units for each author. These ads could either be from your own ad networks (AdSense, or whatever program you are using) or you could get the ads from your authors, in case they have their own accounts.</p>\n<p>You also need to create the ads that show up for your account.</p>\n<h2>2. Set the <em>Author</em> Display Condition</h2>\n<p>In order to attach a specific ad to an author, you must use the <em>Author</em> Display Condition. Once you added it in the <em>Display Conditions</em> meta box, you can select the author to which this ad belongs. This will make sure, that the ad will only show up on posts where this user is the author.</p>\n<figure id=\"attachment_12619\" style=\"width: 435px\" class=\"wp-caption aligncenter\"><a href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/author-display-condition.png\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-12619\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-12619\" src=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/author-display-condition.png\" alt=\"author display condition with Thomas selected\" width=\"435\" height=\"41\" srcset=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/author-display-condition.png 435w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/author-display-condition-300x28.png 300w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/author-display-condition-60x6.png 60w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/author-display-condition-150x14.png 150w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 435px) 100vw, 435px\" /></a><figcaption class=\"wp-caption-text\">This ad would show only on posts written by Thomas</figcaption></figure>\n<h2>3. Create a group</h2>\n<p>Now, create a new ad group from the <em>random</em> type. You might name it by the author. Assign the authors ad and your own ad to this group. Make sure that the ad weight is set up accordingly. For a 20:80 share you would choose 2 for the authors ad and 8 for your own. 1:4 would work too.</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/author-share-group.png\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-12620\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-12620\" src=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/author-share-group.png\" alt=\"author share group\" width=\"180\" height=\"139\" srcset=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/author-share-group.png 180w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/author-share-group-60x46.png 60w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/author-share-group-150x116.png 150w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 180px) 100vw, 180px\" /></a></p>\n<h2>4. Implement the group</h2>\n<p>The last step is to implement the group.</p>\n<p>If you have multiple authors and want to display the ad on the same spot, you need to use a little trick.</p>\n<p>Create another ad for each group. This ad should also have the author display condition set, be of the <em>Rich Content</em> type and only the shortcode of that group in the text field.</p>\n<p>Now, create a meta group with all these intermediate ads in it and place it whereever you want.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/manage-revenue-share-on-mulit-author-blogs/\">Manage revenue share on multi-author blogs  ads per author</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com\">Advanced Ads</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:3;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:39:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n		\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:3:{s:0:\"\";a:6:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:52:\"Using AdSense and other Ads in the Genesis Framework\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:56:\"https://wpadvancedads.com/adsense-ads-genesis-framework/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Wed, 20 Jan 2016 14:30:24 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:3:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:9:\"Tutorials\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:11:\"Genesis Ads\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:10:\"Placements\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:33:\"https://wpadvancedads.com/?p=9779\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:408:\"<p>Genesis and AdSense work great together. Learn from this tutorial how Advanced Ads and the free Genesis Ads plugin can help you with an easy to use interface.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/adsense-ads-genesis-framework/\">Using AdSense and other Ads in the Genesis Framework</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com\">Advanced Ads</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:6:\"Thomas\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:2617:\"<p>The Genesis Framework is a very powerful tool to build great websites with WordPress. Many theme developers already build their customization on top of it. If you display ads from AdSense or other ad networks on your site, Genesis is also a great choice because it makes it simple to add and place the ad units in various positions without the need for additional coding.</p>\n<p>The reason Genesis and AdSense work so great together are hooks. They are placeholders who allow you to target specific positions for any content, not only AdSense ads.</p>\n<p>If you are interested in playing with hooks in WordPress and PHP then follow the <a href=\"https://www.smashingmagazine.com/2016/01/get-started-with-hooks-wordpress/\" target=\"_blank\">tutorial I wrote for Smashing Magazine</a>.</p>\n<p>In case you are less tech-savviy or just want to get the job done quickly, the <a href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/add-ons/genesis-ads/\">free Genesis Ads add-on</a> for Advanced Ads makes use of that built-in technique and gives it an interface.</p>\n<p>After you created an ad you head over to the <em>Placements</em> page and create a new <em>Genesis</em> placement choosing the placement type with the following image.</p>\n<p><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-4905\" src=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/edd/2015/10/genesis.png\" alt=\"Genesis logo\" width=\"180\" height=\"135\" srcset=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/edd/2015/10/genesis.png 180w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/edd/2015/10/genesis-60x45.png 60w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/edd/2015/10/genesis-150x113.png 150w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 180px) 100vw, 180px\" /></p>\n<p>Next, choose any of the positions available in the placement options. You can find a list of them through the <a href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/add-ons/genesis-ads/\" target=\"_blank\">add-on page</a>.</p>\n<p>After saving the options, your ad should be already visible.</p>\n<p>If your ad doesnt show up then beside the <a href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/manual/common-issues/\" target=\"_blank\">common issues</a> it might happen that the theme you chose does not make use of all the documented hooks that normally come with the framework. In that case take a look at the other <a href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/manual/placements/\" target=\"_blank\">available placements</a> in Advanced Ads.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/adsense-ads-genesis-framework/\">Using AdSense and other Ads in the Genesis Framework</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com\">Advanced Ads</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:4;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:33:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:3:{s:0:\"\";a:6:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:38:\"How can I apply custom CSS to my Blog?\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:64:\"https://wpadvancedads.com/how-can-i-apply-custom-css-to-my-blog/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Wed, 13 Jan 2016 09:53:26 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:9:\"Tutorials\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:33:\"https://wpadvancedads.com/?p=9412\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:343:\"<p>This tutorial lists different methods on how to use custom CSS rules in your blog and insert them. </p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/how-can-i-apply-custom-css-to-my-blog/\">How can I apply custom CSS to my Blog?</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com\">Advanced Ads</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:6:\"Thomas\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:3317:\"<p>Displaying ads on your site is also always an interference with the layout. You might therefore often have requirements for ad placements that can not be handles automatically with the options in Advaned Ads. In support, we might then suggest to use custom CSS rules. This tutorial explains how you can write those.</p>\n<p>This tutorial is no introduction into CSS, the language for styling websites. For basic information <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cascading_Style_Sheets\">read more on Wikipedia</a>.</p>\n<h2>Where can I insert CSS?</h2>\n<p>You have various options to insert custom CSS.</p>\n<h3>Use the style.css of your theme</h3>\n<p>Every theme comes with a style.css file. You can just add your custom CSS code there.</p>\n<p>However, this change might be overridden with the next update of a theme and other developers and users might also not find those changes easily.</p>\n<h3>Using theme options</h3>\n<p>Many professional themes come with an option to insert custom CSS or code into the head section of your website.</p>\n<p>This option can often be found within the theme option panel, which is at a different place depending on your theme. Please refer to the manual or ask the developer of the theme for guidance.</p>\n<p>These options dont get overridden on a theme update, but of course are only bound to the current theme and dont apply if you change it.</p>\n<h3>Using a Header Code placement in Advanced Ads</h3>\n<p>Advanced Ads itself comes with a <em>Header Code</em> placement which is intended to manage ad tags that need to be loaded in the <pre class=\"crayon-plain-tag\">head</pre> section of the page. However, this can also be used to inject custom CSS rules into your site and preserve them through theme updates.</p>\n<p>To create such custom code, first create an ad of the <em>Plain Text</em> ad type and wrap the css rules in <pre class=\"crayon-plain-tag\">&lt;style&gt;&lt;/style&gt;</pre> tags. No other settings for the ad are needed.</p>\n<p>Now go to <em>Advanced Ads &gt; Placements</em> and create a Header Code placement. Assign the ad there too and save the placements to publish it.</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/header.png\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-2559\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-2559\" src=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/header.png\" alt=\"header\" width=\"180\" height=\"135\" srcset=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/header.png 180w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/header-60x45.png 60w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/header-150x113.png 150w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 180px) 100vw, 180px\" /></a></p>\n<h2>How can I target ads for styling?</h2>\n<p>CSS is always targeted towards a specific element in the frontend. If you need the ad to have a specific ID or CLASS parameter, insert them either in the appropriate fields in the ad settings or use a placement.</p>\n<p>Placements are automatically wrapped with a container that has a class attribute derrived from the placement title.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/how-can-i-apply-custom-css-to-my-blog/\">How can I apply custom CSS to my Blog?</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com\">Advanced Ads</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:5;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:33:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:3:{s:0:\"\";a:6:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:34:\"How to open an ad in a new window?\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:48:\"https://wpadvancedads.com/open-ad-in-new-window/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Mon, 04 Jan 2016 18:49:08 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:9:\"Tutorials\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:33:\"https://wpadvancedads.com/?p=8630\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:325:\"<p>In this tutorial I will show you how you can open a link in an ad in a new window using Advanced Ads.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/open-ad-in-new-window/\">How to open an ad in a new window?</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com\">Advanced Ads</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:6:\"Thomas\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:3806:\"<p>Opening an ad in a new window or browser tab is a good idea if you dont want to lose visitors entirely to the advertisers page, but still keep them on your site too.</p>\n<p>In this tutorial I will show you how you can accomplish this with Advanced Ads. It basically depends on the ad type and can also be done using an add-on.</p>\n<h2>1. Plain Text ads</h2>\n<p>If you are using the <em>Plain Text and Code</em> ad type, you can simply add some attributes to the link tag to open it in a new window.</p>\n<p>For example, change</p><pre class=\"crayon-plain-tag\">&lt;a href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com\"&gt;Anchor Text&lt;/a&gt;</pre><p>\nto</p><pre class=\"crayon-plain-tag\">&lt;a href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com\" target=\"_blank\"&gt;Anchor Text&lt;/a&gt;</pre><p>\nThe<pre class=\"crayon-plain-tag\">target=\"_blank\"</pre> attribute tells your browser to open the link in a new browser tab or window.</p>\n<p>Keep in mind that ad networks that provide ad code in JavaScript normally dont allow you to modify the code so that it opens in a new window (e.g., AdSense doesnt).</p>\n<h2>2. Rich Media ads</h2>\n<p>If you are using the <em>Rich Media</em> ad type, you can simply highlight a text that you want to link and click on the link icon in the toolbar. The popup that opens for you to select the link target url and the anchor text also contains a checkbox that you can enable in order to open the link in a new window / tab.</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/link-text-blank.png\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-8631\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-8631\" src=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/link-text-blank.png\" alt=\"open link in new window option\" width=\"471\" height=\"128\" srcset=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/link-text-blank.png 471w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/link-text-blank-300x82.png 300w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/link-text-blank-60x16.png 60w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/link-text-blank-150x41.png 150w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 471px) 100vw, 471px\" /></a></p>\n<h2>3. Open all ads in a new window</h2>\n<p>An option that workes for all other ad types (especially Image ads) is included in the <a href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/add-ons/tracking/\" target=\"_blank\">Tracking add-on</a>.</p>\n<p>Once you have that plugin installed you can choose whether all automatically created links should open in a new window or not.</p>\n<p>Go to <em>Advanced Ads &gt; Settings &gt; Tracking</em> and check the option below.</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/tracking-new-window.png\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-8632\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-8632\" src=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/tracking-new-window.png\" alt=\"option to open all links in a new window\" width=\"801\" height=\"56\" srcset=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/tracking-new-window.png 801w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/tracking-new-window-300x21.png 300w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/tracking-new-window-60x4.png 60w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/tracking-new-window-150x10.png 150w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 801px) 100vw, 801px\" /></a></p>\n<p>Keep in mind that only automatically created links will open in a new window. If you track with the link tag hard coded into the ad code (plain text or rich media ad type), you would still need to modify the existing link tag like described in option 1 and 2 above.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/open-ad-in-new-window/\">How to open an ad in a new window?</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com\">Advanced Ads</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:6;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:42:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n		\n		\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:3:{s:0:\"\";a:6:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:46:\"How to place ads in the header of your website\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:54:\"https://wpadvancedads.com/place-ads-in-website-header/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Fri, 11 Dec 2015 10:24:05 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:4:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:9:\"Tutorials\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:16:\"Advanced Ads Pro\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:7:\"Genesis\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:3;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:10:\"Placements\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:33:\"https://wpadvancedads.com/?p=7830\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:342:\"<p>Four methods to place an ad into the header of your website, with or without the need to write code.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/place-ads-in-website-header/\">How to place ads in the header of your website</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com\">Advanced Ads</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:6:\"Thomas\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:8882:\"<p>Many users asked me how they could place an ad into the upper part of their website. This article should cover all the options you currently have with Advanced Ads.</p>\n<h2>What is the website header?</h2>\n<p>It depends on your theme what the header really is, but one could say that it is the upper visible part of your website that doesnt change (much) on all pages. It often contains a logo or navigation. For wpadvancedads.com, I would consider the green highlighted area on the screenshot to be the header.</p>\n<p><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-7833 size-medium\" src=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/header-300x121.png\" alt=\"website header\" width=\"300\" height=\"121\" srcset=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/header-300x121.png 300w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/header-768x311.png 768w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/header-1024x414.png 1024w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/header-60x24.png 60w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/header-150x61.png 150w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/header.png 1150w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px\" /></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h3>header vs. head</h3>\n<p>You might sometimes need to place an ad code into the head part of your website. This shouldnt be confused with the header. The head is the invisible part at the top of your websites source code and no place for visible ads. Some ad networks or servers like DFP need to place code there that pre-loads content that is displayed later.</p>\n<h2>Methods to place an ad into the header</h2>\n<p>These are the basic methods to put an ad that is managed with Advanced Ads into the header:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>PHP function / Manual Placement</li>\n<li>Theme option</li>\n<li>Custom Position placement</li>\n<li>Genesis placements</li>\n</ol>\n<h3>1. PHP function / Manual Placement</h3>\n<p>If you are familiar with PHP and know how WordPress themes are working, you can place the ad manually into the header of your site.</p>\n<p>You can either use the function for an ad <pre class=\"crayon-plain-tag\">the_ad()</pre>, a group <pre class=\"crayon-plain-tag\">the_ad_group()</pre>, or a placement <pre class=\"crayon-plain-tag\">the_ad_placement()</pre>.</p>\n<p>I personally prefer to use the <em>Manual Placement</em>, because once you set it up, it can stay there forever and you can change the ads or group that should appear there from your dashboard, without touching the source code ever again.</p>\n<p>To use the Manual Placement go to <em>Advanced Ads &gt; Placements</em> and create a new placement with the type that is represented by the following image:</p>\n<p><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-2560\" src=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/manual.png\" alt=\"manual placement\" width=\"180\" height=\"135\" srcset=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/manual.png 180w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/manual-60x45.png 60w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/manual-150x113.png 150w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 180px) 100vw, 180px\" /></p>\n<p>Choose a name that helps you remembering where you are going to place the ad and choose the ad or group that should be displayed, if you created it already.</p>\n<p>Now, open the template file with the header code in it. This is very likely the <pre class=\"crayon-plain-tag\">header.php</pre> file in your theme folder. From there on you must find your way to the position in the code where you want to place the ad.</p>\n<p>You can get the PHP code for the placement by clicking on the <em>show usage</em> link on the placement page. However, I prefer the following extended version of that code to make sure that it doesnt break your site if Advanced Ads is not available:</p><pre class=\"crayon-plain-tag\">&lt;?php if( function_exists( \'the_ad_placement\' ) ){\r\nthe_ad_placement(\'PLACEMENT_SLUG\');\r\n} ?&gt;</pre><p>\nBe sure to replace the second line with what you find below the <em>show usage</em> link on the placement page.</p>\n<p>Save the template file and you are ready to make use of this placement.</p>\n<h3>Child Themes</h3>\n<p>One problem you might run into with this method are updates of your theme. When you replace the changed file with a new version, your changes will be lost. So if possible, <a href=\"https://codex.wordpress.org/Child_Themes\">create a child theme</a> for such manual changes.</p>\n<h3>2. Theme option</h3>\n<p>There are many themes out there which already provide basic ad placements and options to put content into a predefined position in the header.</p>\n<p>This varies a lot from theme to theme, so I can only give general advice here.</p>\n<p>Most important is to check, whether these fields accept shortcodes or PHP functions. If they accept shortcodes, create a Manual Placement like described above. Instead of using the PHP function that you find below the <em>show usage</em> link, get the shortcode and place it in the theme option for the header.</p>\n<p>If your theme accepts PHP code, but not a shortcode, use the PHP code from above. However, using the shortcode should always be the preferred choice.</p>\n<h3>3. Custom Position placement</h3>\n<p>The Custom Position placement lets you choose any position in your theme for your ads. It is the best way if you want to be most flexible and are not experienced with coding. It also works after theme updates.</p>\n<p>This placement comes with <a href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/add-ons/advanced-ads-pro/\">Advanced Ads Pro</a> and has this symbol:</p>\n<p><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-3463\" src=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/custom-position.png\" alt=\"custom ad position placement\" width=\"180\" height=\"135\" srcset=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/custom-position.png 180w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/custom-position-60x45.png 60w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/custom-position-150x113.png 150w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 180px) 100vw, 180px\" /></p>\n<p>There is a dedicated page in the manual which also includes a video on how to use this placement:</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/manual/custom-position-placement/\">Custom Position placement</a></p>\n<h3>4. Insert ads into Genesis Theme header</h3>\n<p>Many publishers are using the Genesis theme framework or a child theme built on top of this. The Genesis theme comes with many hooks that allow you to insert content on very different positions.</p>\n<p>However, not all child themes offer an interface to make use of this, so I wrote the <a href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/add-ons/genesis-ads/\">Genesis placement add-on</a>.</p>\n<p>This add-on offers a placement that allows you to target the hooks. There are a few header positions included too, which you can test in order to move your ad to the correct position.</p>\n<p>When choosing this option to place the ad in your websites header, just look out for this placement symbol:</p>\n<p><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-4905\" src=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/edd/2015/10/genesis.png\" alt=\"Genesis logo\" width=\"180\" height=\"135\" srcset=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/edd/2015/10/genesis.png 180w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/edd/2015/10/genesis-60x45.png 60w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/edd/2015/10/genesis-150x113.png 150w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 180px) 100vw, 180px\" /></p>\n<h2>Is the header a good ad position?</h2>\n<p>Finally, I would like to share my opinion as a publisher and consultant about the header position with you.</p>\n<p>If you are using performance based ads (where you get paid for clicks or other actions), the header position is a sub-optimal placement. The reason is simply that people are interested in the content of your site, not the header. They also quickly learn which elements are there and dont look at this position anymore.</p>\n<p>If you work with AdSense and check the active view stats, you might even find that this metric, showing how many times the ad was visible for a second, is quite low. The reason is that people quickly scroll down to see the real content. The smaller the device, the shorter the time spend on the header is.</p>\n<p>The more new visitors you have, the better the performance of the header ads might actually be. It is also a good position for internal ads or the ones that dont need to be clicked in order to earn you money. In fact, some ad networks like their ads there too, despite the rather low performance.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/place-ads-in-website-header/\">How to place ads in the header of your website</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com\">Advanced Ads</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:7;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:36:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:3:{s:0:\"\";a:6:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:41:\"How to limit the ad impressions or clicks\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:57:\"https://wpadvancedads.com/limit-ad-impressions-or-clicks/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Mon, 07 Dec 2015 15:32:28 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:2:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:9:\"Tutorials\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:8:\"Tracking\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:33:\"https://wpadvancedads.com/?p=7695\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:328:\"<p>How to set up an ad with limited impressions or clicks using Advanced Ads for WordPress.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/limit-ad-impressions-or-clicks/\">How to limit the ad impressions or clicks</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com\">Advanced Ads</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:6:\"Thomas\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:2300:\"<p>When you sell ads directly or just want to test the performance of new ads, you might want to display them not only for a specific time, but also for a specific amout of impressions or clicks.</p>\n<p>This is very easy to set up using the <a href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/add-ons/tracking/\">Tracking add-on</a>.</p>\n<h2>Setup</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>WordPress 4.3</li>\n<li>Advanced Ads plugin installed</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/add-ons/tracking/\">Tracking add-on</a> installed</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Limit ad impressions or clicks</h2>\n<p>Go to <em>Advanced Ads &gt; Ads</em> in your WordPress dashboard and select the ad you want to limit.</p>\n<p>Scroll down to the <em>Stats</em> meta box. It might look similar to this:</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/ad-limits.png\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-7696\" src=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/ad-limits.png\" alt=\"ad stats metabox\" width=\"524\" height=\"176\" srcset=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/ad-limits.png 524w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/ad-limits-300x101.png 300w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/ad-limits-60x20.png 60w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/ad-limits-150x50.png 150w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 524px) 100vw, 524px\" /></a></p>\n<p>If you change the values in the <em>limit</em> column to anything above 0 and save the ad, the limit is used.</p>\n<p>The ad is not showing up anymore when the first limit is reached. You can manually increase the limit or reset the stats to show it again.</p>\n<h2>Check the calculation of the limits</h2>\n<p>In order to limit the impact on the sites performance, the real ad impressions and clicks are not summed up with every page impression. By default, this happens every 60 minutes.</p>\n<p>To change this, go to <em>Advanced Ads &gt; Settings &gt; Tracking</em> and adjust the value for the<em>Recalculate sums</em> setting. The lower the number, the higher might be the impact on your performance.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/limit-ad-impressions-or-clicks/\">How to limit the ad impressions or clicks</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com\">Advanced Ads</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:8;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:42:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:5:{s:0:\"\";a:7:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:48:\"Advanced Ads 1.6.14 allows editors to manage ads\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:46:\"https://wpadvancedads.com/advanced-ads-1-6-14/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:55:\"https://wpadvancedads.com/advanced-ads-1-6-14/#comments\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Mon, 07 Dec 2015 11:58:20 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:14:\"Update Notices\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:33:\"https://wpadvancedads.com/?p=7679\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:310:\"<p>Allow editors to create and manage ads in WordPress with Advanced Ads now.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/advanced-ads-1-6-14/\">Advanced Ads 1.6.14 allows editors to manage ads</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com\">Advanced Ads</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:6:\"Thomas\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:2316:\"<p>The latest update of Advanced Ads allows you to give editors the right to manage ads. This includes everything except changing general options and working with the support page.</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/editors-manage-ads.png\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-7680\" src=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/editors-manage-ads.png\" alt=\"option to allow editors to manage ads\" width=\"534\" height=\"70\" srcset=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/editors-manage-ads.png 534w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/editors-manage-ads-300x39.png 300w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/editors-manage-ads-60x8.png 60w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/editors-manage-ads-150x20.png 150w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 534px) 100vw, 534px\" /></a></p>\n<p>The option is disabled by default, so if you dont touch anything, nothing will change for you.</p>\n<h2>Which capabilities do you want to set?</h2>\n<p>Technically, this change wasnt big, but it opened the door to fine tune capabilities. However, before putting more effort into this, I would like to know if this is even interesting for you?</p>\n<p>Do you want normal authors to be able to use any of the features from Advanced Ads? Do you want some ad editors not to be able to use HTML, JavaScript or PHP in their ads? Or maybe you want to manage capabilities on a per-user basis?</p>\n<p>There are so many possiblities, so for the first time ever on this site, I opened the comments below this post and invite you to leave an idea regarding this there.</p>\n<p><strong>Please use the comment form below to let me know if you need a specific capability</strong> <img src=\"https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/72x72/1f642.png\" alt=\"?\" class=\"wp-smiley\" style=\"height: 1em; max-height: 1em;\" /></p>\n<p>I am going to update the other add-ons during this week, so that editors that can manage ads can also see the stats of the <a href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/add-ons/tracking/\">Tracking add-on</a>.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/advanced-ads-1-6-14/\">Advanced Ads 1.6.14 allows editors to manage ads</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com\">Advanced Ads</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:36:\"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/\";a:1:{s:10:\"commentRss\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:51:\"https://wpadvancedads.com/advanced-ads-1-6-14/feed/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:38:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/\";a:1:{s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1:\"9\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:9;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:36:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:3:{s:0:\"\";a:6:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:49:\"How to create an anchor ad with a slide-in effect\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:48:\"https://wpadvancedads.com/anchor-ad-with-effect/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Tue, 24 Nov 2015 12:50:40 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:2:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:9:\"Tutorials\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:10:\"Sticky Ads\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:33:\"https://wpadvancedads.com/?p=7121\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:351:\"<p>This tutorial shows how to create an anchor or sticky ad with different effects in WordPress using Advanced Ads.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/anchor-ad-with-effect/\">How to create an anchor ad with a slide-in effect</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com\">Advanced Ads</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:6:\"Thomas\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:3263:\"<p>In this tutorial I am going to show you how you can create an anchor ad with an effect, like fade-in or slide-in.</p>\n<h2>Video (3:18 min)</h2>\n<p><a href=\"https://youtu.be/TwFbV04CW0M?hd=1&amp;autoplay=1\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-7854\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-medium wp-image-7854\" src=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/advancedads-start-video-300x135.png\" alt=\"Start Video\" width=\"300\" height=\"135\" srcset=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/advancedads-start-video-300x135.png 300w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/advancedads-start-video-1024x462.png 1024w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/advancedads-start-video-60x27.png 60w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/advancedads-start-video-150x68.png 150w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px\" /></a></p>\n<h2>Setup used in this tutorial</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>Advanced Ads v. 1.6.12</li>\n<li>Advanced Ads  <a href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/add-ons/sticky-ads/\" target=\"_blank\">Sticky Ads</a> v. 1.4.5</li>\n<li>WordPress 4.3.1</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Video Transcript</h2>\n<p>In this tutorial I want to show you how you can create an Anchor Ad or a Sticky Ad with a small effect. First, you need to make sure that you have Advanced Ads and <a href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/add-ons/sticky-ads/\">Advanced Ads Sticky Ads</a> activated in your plugins. For Sticky Ads we need at least version 1.4.5.</p>\n<h3>Creating the ad</h3>\n<p>Head over to our <em>Ad</em> section. In order to create a new ad, we&#8217;ll just call it <em>Anchor Ad</em> and choose the image ad as the ad type. Now select an image and a url to link to.</p>\n<p>There&#8217;s nothing else you need to set up in order to create an anchor ad from this. So you can already publish it.</p>\n<h3>Create the Anchor Placement</h3>\n<p>Go to <em>Advanced Ads &gt; Placements</em> and choose the <em>Footer Bar</em> from the available placements. As a name, you can also choose &#8220;Anchor Ad&#8221;. You should also select the ad that and save the placement.</p>\n<p>If you head over to the front end, you would now see an anchor ad.</p>\n<h3>Adding the effect</h3>\n<p>In order to add the effect, you need to open the <em>advanced options</em>. There you can see two sections. The first one lets you choose the trigger, the action that is triggering the ad to show up.</p>\n<p>You can either show up the ad right away, using an effect or whether to display the ad after a few seconds.</p>\n<p>The next section is about the effect itself. The <em>Show</em> action is more or less showing the ad directly. You can also fade it in or slide it in.</p>\n<p>To see how each of them looks like, you can check &#8220;F<em>ade in</em>. You also need to choose how many milliseconds the effect will last. You can experiment with this.</p>\n<p>Choosing 1,000 would mean that the effect will happen over a period of one second.</p>\n<p>If you save the placements again and go to your frontend, wait a (few) seconds, the ad is fading in.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/anchor-ad-with-effect/\">How to create an anchor ad with a slide-in effect</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com\">Advanced Ads</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:10;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:33:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:3:{s:0:\"\";a:6:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:26:\"Using responsive image ads\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:54:\"https://wpadvancedads.com/create-responsive-image-ads/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Tue, 24 Nov 2015 08:58:23 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:10:\"Background\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:33:\"https://wpadvancedads.com/?p=7098\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:336:\"<p>How Advanced Ads uses the new responsive images feature in WordPress to optimize image ads for responsive layouts.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/create-responsive-image-ads/\">Using responsive image ads</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com\">Advanced Ads</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:6:\"Thomas\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:5705:\"<p>Since WordPress 4.4 and Advanced Ads 1.6.13, Ad Images and images used in the Rich Content ad type can be responsive. This means that they dont just get scaled down, but the browser in fact loads a smaller file size, if it is available. This makes your ad load faster on devices with a smaller screen or a slower internet connection.</p>\n<p>The feature of responsive images comes with WordPress and Advanced Ads supports that out of the box for ads within the main content. However, in order to get the most out of this, you need to know a few things.</p>\n<h2>Why responsive images?</h2>\n<p>For many websites, traffic from mobile devices is already bigger than from desktop devices. Responsive layouts have made it possible to deliver the same content to mobile and desktop visitors without an extra effort for publishers. However, bandwidth is still a problem, since mobile connections arent as fast and reliable as normal connections. The problem is especially big if you deliver many high resolution images.</p>\n<p>There are and have been different solutions for this problem. In most cases this took extra effort to implement too. With WordPress 4.4, this problem was addressed and publishers now might rely in it  if theme developers start to support it.</p>\n<h2>How does WordPress generate responsive images?</h2>\n<p>Without going too deep into the code, lets just say that WordPress adds extra attributes to the source code that displays the images (for coders: adding <pre class=\"crayon-plain-tag\">srcset</pre> and <pre class=\"crayon-plain-tag\">sizes</pre> to <pre class=\"crayon-plain-tag\">img</pre> tags). These attributes contain links to images in different sizes so that browsers, who understand these attributes, can choose the smallest file size that is large enough to fit.</p>\n<p>When are these images generated?</p>\n<p>WordPress creates multiple sizes of images when you upload them. This by itself is not a new feature. You can go to <em>Dashboard &gt; Settings &gt; Media</em> to see which image sizes are created by default.</p>\n<p>Keep in mind that with WordPress 4.4 there is also another, not visible, image size with 768px in width and without height restriction added.</p>\n<p>WordPress creates the tags for responsive attributes only for images in the content. I have applied the same feature now to all ads with the Image Ad type and images in the Rich Media ad type that get displayed within the content.</p>\n<h2>Issues with responsive image ads</h2>\n<p>If you are a developer, you should read the <a href=\"https://make.wordpress.org/core/2015/11/10/responsive-images-in-wordpress-4-4/\">announcement post</a> for responsive images in order to learn more about the possibilites and issues.</p>\n<h3>Adding image sizes</h3>\n<p>WordPress creates only the image sizes set up either in <em>Dashboard &gt; Settings &gt; Media</em>, by a plugin or your theme or uses the new default size with 768px width. If you think that another size would be better in your case, you should either add a new one or change the existing settings.</p>\n<p>However, WordPress does only create the added or changed sizes for new images. To regenerate previous images, you need to use a plugin like <a href=\"https://de.wordpress.org/plugins/regenerate-thumbnails/\">Regenerate Thumbnails</a>.</p>\n<h3>Themes not making use of this</h3>\n<p>Using one of the new attributes (<pre class=\"crayon-plain-tag\">srcset</pre>), browsers now know the available image sizes. However, they dont know yet which images fit. Imagine, that a theme is 500px wide, but has a margin of 25px left and right, so the available space in the content is only 450px. Browsers might not know this at the time the image is requested, so there is another attribute (<pre class=\"crayon-plain-tag\">sizes</pre>) which can be influenced by themes.</p>\n<p>The new default theme twentysixteen already makes use of it, but if you are using another or a custom developed theme, you need to ask the developer if he could implement support for responsive images. Without that, neither WordPress nor Advanced Ads can help to optimize images for specific sizes.</p>\n<h3>Responsive image ads in Advanced Ads</h3>\n<p>Advanced Ads is one of the first plugins supporting responsive image ads. However, it mostly depends on your settings and theme, if this is used with most benefits. I expect a lot to happen in this field and will wait for your feedback and how theme developers implement support for responsive images, before extending this feature with more options.</p>\n<p>In case you have issues with responsive image ads, you can disable them by defining the <pre class=\"crayon-plain-tag\">ADVADS_DISABLE_RESPONSIVE_IMAGES</pre> constant in your wp-config.php.</p>\n<h3>Responsive images with CSS</h3>\n<p>In case you have troubles implementing responsive images programmatically like described above, you can make use of a simple CSS trick. The line below will adapt images optically to the available width if the screen becomes narrower than the image itself.</p>\n<p>This is just an example for images within the content area in standard themes. If your theme has other containers (e.g. #main), then adapt it. The developer of the theme can definitely help you with it.</p><pre class=\"crayon-plain-tag\">article img { max-width: 100%; height: auto; }</pre><p>\nRead <a href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/how-can-i-apply-custom-css-to-my-blog/\">this article</a> to learn more about adding custom CSS.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/create-responsive-image-ads/\">Using responsive image ads</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com\">Advanced Ads</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:11;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:33:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:3:{s:0:\"\";a:6:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:68:\"How to insert Google DoubleClick for Publishers (DFP) into WordPress\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:63:\"https://wpadvancedads.com/doubleclick-for-publishers-wordpress/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Fri, 23 Oct 2015 09:24:59 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:9:\"Tutorials\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:33:\"https://wpadvancedads.com/?p=5718\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:402:\"<p>In this video tutorial you will learn how to implement Google DoubleClick for Publishers (DFP) into WordPress using Advanced Ads.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/doubleclick-for-publishers-wordpress/\">How to insert Google DoubleClick for Publishers (DFP) into WordPress</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com\">Advanced Ads</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:6:\"Thomas\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:13139:\"<p>In this video tutorial you will learn how to implement Google DoubleClick for Publishers (DFP) into WordPress using Advanced Ads.</p>\n<p>I am also going to cover the disadvantages of the separation of header and body tags and how to solve them.</p>\n<h2>Video (9:26 min)</h2>\n<figure id=\"attachment_7869\" style=\"width: 300px\" class=\"wp-caption aligncenter\"><a href=\"https://youtu.be/oaD9xYfXcGg?hd=1&amp;amp;autoplay=1\"><img class=\"wp-image-7869 size-medium\" src=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/advancedads-implementing-dfp-300x169.jpg\" alt=\"Start Video\" width=\"300\" height=\"169\" srcset=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/advancedads-implementing-dfp-300x169.jpg 300w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/advancedads-implementing-dfp-1024x576.jpg 1024w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/advancedads-implementing-dfp-60x34.jpg 60w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/advancedads-implementing-dfp-150x84.jpg 150w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px\" /></a><figcaption class=\"wp-caption-text\">(click to start)</figcaption></figure>\n<h2>Setup used in this tutorial</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>Advanced Ads, version 1.6.10.2, <a href=\"https://downloads.wordpress.org/plugin/advanced-ads.1.6.10.2.zip\">Download for free</a></li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Further reading</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>DFP: <a href=\"https://support.google.com/dfp_sb/answer/82283?hl=en\" target=\"_blank\">Generate ad tags in DFP</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/manual/first-ad/\">How to create and display your first ad</a> with Advanced Ads</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Inserting Google DFP into WordPress</h2>\n<p>In this article, we will show you how to implements ad texts from Google DFP (Double Click for Publishers) into your WordPress CMS using advanced ads. DFP is a powerful web server used for serving ads to end users. It is especially useful for tailoring by geolocation and other demographics. Throughout the rest of the article, we will assume you are already using this function and know how to use Google DFP tags and how to get them.</p>\n<h3>Managing DFP tags</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/dfp-tags.png\"><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-6291 size-large\" src=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/dfp-tags-1024x556.png\" alt=\"dfp tags\" width=\"980\" height=\"532\" srcset=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/dfp-tags-1024x556.png 1024w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/dfp-tags-300x163.png 300w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/dfp-tags-60x33.png 60w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/dfp-tags-150x82.png 150w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 980px) 100vw, 980px\" /></a></p>\n<p>A Google DFP tag is not a single tag as it is on AdSense. It has a header tag and a tag for the ad unit. The header tag contains information about the loaded ads, including their unique IDs, information that we will need in this tutorial.</p>\n<p>In order to set up DFP, we need at least two ad units. The first is for the header tag and the second for each ad.</p>\n<p>Go to <em>Advanced Ads &gt; Ads &gt; Create New Ad</em></p>\n<p>Give your ad a title and select the ad type (plain text code, rich content, image ad, AdSense Ad). We called ours DFP Head. Select plain text code if it is not already pre-selected.</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/insert-dfp-header.png\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-large wp-image-6292\" src=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/insert-dfp-header-1024x555.png\" alt=\"create DFP header code\" width=\"980\" height=\"531\" srcset=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/insert-dfp-header-1024x555.png 1024w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/insert-dfp-header-300x163.png 300w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/insert-dfp-header-60x33.png 60w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/insert-dfp-header-150x81.png 150w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 980px) 100vw, 980px\" /></a></p>\n<p>Bring up the code again and copy the header text from the code box and paste it into the box marked <em>Ad parameters</em>. Typically, you will not need to change anything else so you can publish that ad immediately.</p>\n<p>Next go to Placements on your dashboard and click <em>Create New Placement</em>. You will need to assign it a certain type. The text you just copied was header text so select the Header type. Dont forget to give it a name, then choose the ad or group and save.</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/create-header-placement.png\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-large wp-image-6293\" src=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/create-header-placement-1024x553.png\" alt=\"new header placement form\" width=\"980\" height=\"529\" srcset=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/create-header-placement-1024x553.png 1024w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/create-header-placement-300x162.png 300w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/create-header-placement-60x32.png 60w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/create-header-placement-150x81.png 150w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 980px) 100vw, 980px\" /></a></p>\n<p>The header code should now be on the website.</p>\n<p>Next, you will repeat the process for the ad codes and put them in the front end. Go to <em>Add New Ad</em>, give the ad a name. In this case, we call it Skyscraper. Copy the text from the ad code list  do one for each individual ad, copying only the ad text. As you can see in the image below, we have copied over the short text referring to the skyscraper ad only. We place this in the ad parameters box in the WordPress client on the left hand side of our screen.</p>\n<p>We use fake numbers so we cannot show you how the ad should look, it is just an example.</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/create-body-ad.png\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-large wp-image-6294\" src=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/create-body-ad-1024x559.png\" alt=\"create dfp body ad\" width=\"980\" height=\"535\" srcset=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/create-body-ad-1024x559.png 1024w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/create-body-ad-300x164.png 300w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/create-body-ad-60x33.png 60w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/create-body-ad-150x82.png 150w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 980px) 100vw, 980px\" /></a></p>\n<p>Then click publish to complete the action. You should check them on your website to make sure they look right  for example, placing them in the widget area of WordPress or on a sidebar or wherever else you are placing your ads.</p>\n<h3>Matching Header and Body Code</h3>\n<p>Wed like to take a brief moment to demonstrate a problem with DFP. Imagine you have just published an ad on your WordPress CMS. The header text preloads the ad content; this is useful because when the ad content is added later, it loads much faster than it would if it was just loaded as a separate ad.</p>\n<p>The problem is that Google DFP believes when you preload the ad in the header content, that it ought to display it which means they already count the impression in the DFP server. If you mix up the numbers, you will see nothing. Make sure the text matches between the ad ID in the header text and the ad ID itself.</p>\n<h3>Selecting Locations</h3>\n<p>What if you want to display one ad on all websites but a second just in one location or in a specific category? Not a problem, all you need to do is create two header units in Advanced Ads as described above.</p>\n<p>Create one for the condition for both ads to be displayed, then a separate ad unit. For example in the image below, we have created the header ad but removed the ad that will only appear in one place  just one appears in the text.</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/ad-group.png\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-large wp-image-6295\" src=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/ad-group-1024x558.png\" alt=\"dfp ad group\" width=\"980\" height=\"534\" srcset=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/ad-group-1024x558.png 1024w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/ad-group-300x163.png 300w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/ad-group-60x33.png 60w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/ad-group-150x82.png 150w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 980px) 100vw, 980px\" /></a></p>\n<p>Before publishing it, create a group (on the right of the above image, text is entered into the <em>Ad Groups</em> area). Return to any other ads and add it to the group you just created (if necessary). Then go to <em>Placements</em> in your sidebar and under <em>DFP Header</em> change the option to group from ads.</p>\n<p>This ensures that only one header is selected at any one time.</p>\n<p>Next, create a group for the ad that you want to appear only in one place. Dont publish the group, simply copy over the text from the ad and then scroll down to <em>Display Conditions</em>. Change from <em>Display Ad Everywhere</em> to <em>Set Display Conditions</em>. A series of options will appear.</p>\n<p>In our case, we have chosen to display in the General Category so uncheck the display all categories, tags and taxonomies as displayed in the image above. When unchecked, it should look like the image below.</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/dfp-category-condition.png\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-large wp-image-6297\" src=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/dfp-category-condition-1024x556.png\" alt=\"Check General category\" width=\"980\" height=\"532\" srcset=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/dfp-category-condition-1024x556.png 1024w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/dfp-category-condition-300x163.png 300w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/dfp-category-condition-60x33.png 60w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/dfp-category-condition-150x81.png 150w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 980px) 100vw, 980px\" /></a></p>\n<p>Click General or whichever category you want it to display in. Once this is done, you can publish it. By all means check again that the ad is displayed properly but most importantly, you need to check that the group does not contain the ad that you want to omit. Go back in the ads and double check.</p>\n<p>Note: ensure that the header also has the same display conditions</p>\n<h3>Defining the Order</h3>\n<p>Go to <em>Advanced Ads &gt; Groups</em></p>\n<p>You can see on the right hand side that under ads in the image above (right hand side) there is an ordered list. It is important to ensure that the header code with the most restrictions is loaded first. We use the second one with the two ads in as a fall back should anything not function properly.</p>\n<p>Check the one with the conditions. Click edit on the left hand side and the screen should look like this.</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/dfp-set-up-groups.png\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-large wp-image-6303\" src=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/dfp-set-up-groups-1024x560.png\" alt=\"DFP group setup\" width=\"980\" height=\"536\" srcset=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/dfp-set-up-groups-1024x560.png 1024w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/dfp-set-up-groups-300x164.png 300w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/dfp-set-up-groups-60x33.png 60w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/dfp-set-up-groups-150x82.png 150w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 980px) 100vw, 980px\" /></a></p>\n<p>Click on <em>Ordered ads</em>. At the bottom of the screen, you will see that the ads are ordered. In the image above, both have been set to 10. We only have two options, so we set the one that needs to be checked last to 9 (DFP Head in our list). The highest number always runs first. Anything set to 1 will always come last. It is important to remember this.</p>\n<p>Then save it and you are done.</p>\n<h3>Conclusion</h3>\n<p>The best way to use Google DFP is to have the same ad units on all sites. Its easier if you have them in the header or sidebars but in some cases, you will need to break them up as we explained in the second half of the article, to create different ad setups.</p>\n<p>This is to avoid the problem months later when you notice your click through rates are lower than they should or could be  the problem being that your ad unit is counted too often, more often than it is displayed. It is a problem with Google DFP, but Advanced Ads can help you to solve it like explained above.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com/doubleclick-for-publishers-wordpress/\">How to insert Google DoubleClick for Publishers (DFP) into WordPress</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpadvancedads.com\">Advanced Ads</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}}}s:27:\"http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom\";a:1:{s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:3:{s:4:\"href\";s:31:\"https://wpadvancedads.com/feed/\";s:3:\"rel\";s:4:\"self\";s:4:\"type\";s:19:\"application/rss+xml\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:44:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/syndication/\";a:2:{s:12:\"updatePeriod\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:6:\"hourly\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:15:\"updateFrequency\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}}}}}}}}s:4:\"type\";i:128;s:7:\"headers\";a:15:{s:6:\"server\";s:5:\"nginx\";s:4:\"date\";s:29:\"Thu, 16 Jun 2016 07:36:17 GMT\";s:12:\"content-type\";s:34:\"application/rss+xml; charset=UTF-8\";s:14:\"content-length\";s:5:\"16780\";s:10:\"connection\";s:5:\"close\";s:12:\"x-robots-tag\";s:15:\"noindex, follow\";s:4:\"link\";s:62:\"<https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-json/>; rel=\"https://api.w.org/\"\";s:10:\"set-cookie\";a:2:{i:0;s:99:\"advanced_ads_page_impressions=0; expires=Sun, 30-Dec-1979 00:00:00 GMT; Max-Age=-1150702577; path=/\";i: